Basic Coding With R: Solutions

This document provides solutions to the challenge exercises from “Basic Coding With R.” You might want to make note of two things. First, there may be more than one “right” solution. I provided some straightforward answers, but you may have done something different that still gets the same result. So, as you look through this, don’t worry that your code looks different as long as you got it to do what it is supposed to do. Second, there are commands and functions in this code that you may not know. This happens with coding; you always run into structures or functions that you’re not familiar with. When this happens, remember you can always Google it!

Storing Variables

Challenge: Create the following variables:

  1. A list of the numbers from 101 to 150. Call it ‘index’.
index <- 101:150
  1. A list of 30 TRUE and then 20 FALSE. Call it ‘boo’
boo <- rep(c(TRUE, FALSE), c(30, 20))
  1. A list that switches between “red” and “blue” (e.g., “red”, “blue”) that has length 50 (i.e., 25 reds and 25 blues). Call it ‘colors’
colors <- rep(c("red", "blue"), 25)
  1. A named list that has 3 elements. Each element is a list. The first is ‘index’ from part 1, the second is ‘boo’ from part 2, and the third is ‘colors’ from part 3.
named_list <- list(index = index,
                   boo = boo,
                   colors = colors)

  1. Write a for loop that iterates through numbers from 1 to 50. If the number is divisible by 7, print “BEE”, and if the number is not divisible by 7, print “BUZZ”. (Hint: You may need to use some if statements in your for loop. Also, X %% Y gives you the remainder of dividing X by Y. So, 8 %% 7 is 1, but 14 %% 7 is 0.)
for(i in 1:50){
  
  if(i %% 7 == 0){
    print("BEE")
  } else {
    print("BUZZ")
  }
  
}

  1. Write a for loop that for each number from 1 to 100 prints “PRIME” if the number is a prime number, and “COMPOSITE” if it is not a prime number.
for(i in 1:100){
  
  num = NA
  
  if(i <= 3){
    
    num = NA
    
  } else {
    
    for(j in 2:floor(i/2)){
      
      if(i %% j == 0){
        
        num = "COMPOSITE"
        break()
        
      } 
    }
  }
  
  if(is.na(num)){
    print("PRIME")
  } else {
    print(num)
  }
  
}

Functions and Libraries

  1. Create a list foo of the numbers 1 to 100, bar1 that is the square of the numbers 1 to 100, and bar2 that is the square root of the numbers 1 to 100. Use the plot() function to plot:
foo <- 1:100
bar1 <- foo^2
bar2 <- sqrt(foo)
 - <code>foo</code> versus <code>bar1</code>
 - <code>foo</code> versus <code>bar2</code>
 - <code>bar1</code> versus <code>bar2</code>
plot(foo, bar1) # foo vs bar1

plot(foo, bar2) # foo vs bar1

plot(bar1, bar2) # foo vs bar1

  1. Let’s expand the guess_my_number() function to allow the user to make multiple guesses. You can copy the basic structure of the code, but you’ll have to change the conditionals to include a while loop. (Hint: initialize a variable before the if called num_guesses and use that in your while loop.)
guess_my_number <- function(max_guesses=3){
  
  number = sample.int(10, 1) # the *random* number you try to guess
  
  num_guesses = 0 # start counting the guesses
  
  win = FALSE # set win to FALSE, and only change it to TRUE if you win.
  
  guess <- readline("Guess a number: ") # ask for a guess
  guess <- as.numeric(guess)
  
  while(num_guesses < max_guesses){# if you still have guesses left, keep playing
    
    if(guess == number){ # if you guess correctly, you win

      win = TRUE
      break() # exit out of the while() loop
      
    } else {
      
      num_guesses <- num_guesses + 1 # increment the counter
    
      if(num_guesses < max_guesses){
        
        guess <- readline("That's not right. Guess again: ") # guess again
        guess = as.numeric(guess)
        
      } else {
      
        break()
      
      }
      
    }
    
  }
  
  if(win){
    
    print("You win!")
    
  } else {
    
    print("You lose...")
    
  }
  
  return(NULL) # Return nothing

}

# guess_my_number(5)
